  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering is a serious crime with significant penalties. Here are some key points about potential legal consequences:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Imprisonment up to 20 years\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Potential seizure of assets involved in laundering\n\n2. Specific Sentencing Factors:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Involvement in organized crime\n- Prior criminal history\n- Specific circumstances of the offense\n\n3. Additional Potential Consequences:\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Restitution payments\n- Probation\n- Restrictions on future financial activities\n\n4. Relevant Statutes:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money Laundering)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in Monetary Transactions)\n\nThe exact penalties can vary based on specific details of the case and prosecutorial discretion. For precise legal guidance about a specific situation, consulting a qualified criminal defense attorney is recommended.",
